did.abstract: The Indiana University Division of Student and Educational Services was primarily concerned with the non-academic educational programs of the university. Offices the Division oversaw included the University Press, the School of Letters, and the Conference Bureau. Collection consists of correspondence, subject files, research reports and proposals, committee meeting minutes and files, and memos. Records date from John W. Ashton's tenure as Dean and Vice President of the Division.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: The Division of Student and Educational Services was primarily concerned with the non-academic educational programs of the University. Offices and activities they oversaw included:

list.item: -University's counseling system (with the exception of the Junior Division, which reported directly to the Dean of Faculties)
- Office of the Editor of Publications
- Dean of Students Office, along with its various subdivisions
- Research Center for Anthropology, Folklore, and Linguistics
- representing the University at conferences and special meetings; occasionally assisted in the entertainment of distinguished visitors to the campus

bioghist.p: John W. Ashton was appointed Dean and Director of the Division in 1950 and was given the additional title of Vice President in 1952. Prior to his appointment, he served as Dean of the College of Arts and Sciences from 1946 to 1951 (he gradually assumed his responsibilities as Dean of the Division after being named to that position 1950). In 1958, Ashton left his post with the Division to become Dean of the Graduate School and Vice President for Graduate Development.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The numerous accessions brought together to form this collection had first to be sorted by the positions John Ashton held at the university - Dean and Vice President of the Division of Student and Educational Services (Collection C211), Dean of the College of Arts and Sciences (contact Archives staff), and Vice President for Graduate Development and Dean of the Graduate School (Collection C212) - as the records had been all been filed together. Consequently, it was impossible to discern the original organizational scheme for the records. In most cases, the files retain their original folder title. Exceptions to this are the files in the Correspondence series and some of the files in the Administrative/Subject files series, which were either simply labeled as "John Ashton" or identified by year. In these cases, a more descriptive folder heading was created by the processor.
Restricted files are marked as such and placed at the end of the collection in Box 6.

The records of the Division of Student and Educational Services consists of correspondence, research reports and proposals, committee meeting minutes, and memos organized into six series: Administrative/Subject files; Research; Committees; Correspondence; Conferences and meetings; and Papers and reports.

The Administrative/Subject files series is by far the largest series in the collection comprising nearly 3 cubic feet. The files primarily consist of correspondence on the named subject but also include memos, reports, and publications. Prominent subjects include annual reports, the International Cooperation Administration (ICA), and scholarships. This series is arranged alphabetically by folder title.

The second series, Research, is further organized into three subseries: Correspondence, Proposals and reports, and Subject files. The Correspondence subseries consist of general correspondence regarding research and projects in which the university was participating. Frequent correspondents include university professors and United States agencies such as the United States Dept. of Health, Education and Welfare. The proposals and reports subseries includes a wealth of information about research projects the university and individual professors undertook. The Subject subseries includes quite a bit of information on funding and on the Human Relations Area Files, Inc., an organization founded in 1949 to focus on the field of cultural anthropology.

The Committees series is arranged alphabetically and consists of correspondence, minutes, and notes from the various university and outside committees Ashton served on or corresponded with. By far the most prominent committee is the Research Committee.

The fourth series, Correspondence, includes both incoming and outgoing correspondence of the Division. More frequent correspondents were given their own folder, while others were put in a general folder. Prominent correspondents include Professors Thomas Sebeok and Carlton T. Hodge. The series is arranged alphabetically.

Conferences and meetings is a small series that contains information on conferences Dean Ashton attended or helped organized. Included are five files on the Linguistic Institute, which was sponsored annually by the Linguistic Society of America. It was held at IU the summers of 1952 and 1953. The series is arranged alphabetically.

The final series, papers and reports, consists of just eight folders and contains papers, reports, and publications pulled primarily from "Miscellaneous" files. Some of the files include correspondence relating to the subject of the file. The folders are arranged alphabetically.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into six series: Administrative/Subject files; Research; Committees; Correspondence; Conferences and meetings; and Papers and reports.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: Material removed from this collection includes duplicates and some non-IU publications.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: For more information on John Ashton and the other positions he held at the university see IU Archives Collection C212, the Vice President for Graduate Development and Dean of the Graduate School records, or contact Archives staff regarding his tenure as Dean of the College of Arts and Sciences..
